  }, "should"), " be taxed (based on land size, house size, etc.), we see that reassessed people were being undertaxed before, and moved towards accurate tax levels after being treated."), mdx("p", null, "##Targeting##"), mdx("p", null, "Targeting is figuring out who gets the benefits of some program or policy. This is more difficult to do in developing countries than in wealthy countries, because poorer countries have fewer methods to confirm things like income. People's behavior varies depending on social norms and stigmas, being ostracized or audited, double-reporting or lack of it, etc."), mdx("p", null, "A few methods to clarify people's income brackets include putting them to unpleasant tasks for money and seeing who sticks, going to people's places to gauge where they're at financially, etc. However, these methods have their drawbacks. Just as people can like about consumption, they can hide their possessions. We can somewhat get around this by assessing permanent durables/assets such as land or vehicles. Assets probably don't also tell the whole story. In the US, even income is seen as imperfect because it doesn't say much about earning potential. Similar logic can be applied to proxy-means tests. Surveyors might also be bribed."), mdx("p", null, "When PMT was run in Columbia, people began to adjust such that they'd fall beneath the threshold to be eligible for benefits. This is similar to how factories adjusted to being audited in...China? India? idr."), mdx("p", null, "Then there's community-based targeting, wherein people in a community convene and decide who gets the money. Norms and stigmas may play a role here, but then so does more enforcement and less lying. A community might lie as a group, however. Social dominance might sway the direction the money goes and result in \"elites capturing\" it. Therefore there's a tradeoff between telling the locals what you're up to and getting better information, and elite capture."), mdx("p", null, "###Survey in Indonesia###"), mdx("p", null, "Comparing PMT and Community Approaches (Alatas, Banerjee, Hanna, Olken, Tobias) (refer to slide for model) - proxy vs community targeting etc, teasing out elite capture vs preferences etc"), mdx("p", null, "600 randomly chossen villages, $3 transfers. Testing 3 targeting methods: Community rankings, meaning community deliberates as to who's poorest; proxy-means tests; hybrid testing means community ranking, then measure bottom 50% with proxy-means tests."), mdx("p", null, "Consumption is hard to gauge, so using that as a metric can be finnicky. It has more predictive power for the poorest than for the richest, however (they'd have a hard time eating their huge amount of money)."), mdx("p", null, "Community targeting effective.\n", "[review this/read papers]"), mdx("p", null, "One way to implement self-targeting is through programs that have an unpleasantness or high cost to entering them. This is a fine balancing act though since it can backfire; for example, if you want people to self-select themselves by working through grueling documentation, that's all well and good, but if the people you're seeking to target have poor documentation to begin with, we're screening in the opposite direction. Screening and applications processes may be a hassle, food stamps might restrict choices, or going into low-income housing. NREGA in India guaranteed people 100 days of manual labor at minimum wage."), mdx("p", null, "If we're trying to determine the chances of passing a proxy means test (PMT), we can use a couple of variables. One variable would be observable income like permanent assets, roofing, tiles, etc. The other would be unobservable income, where people might keep things hidden. We may also get indicators of this by asking innocent questions on consumption, where the surveyed have no incentive to lie.  With this latter variable, our probability of passing the PMT won't go down as steeply as with observed income. This is because people ca